            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Sarah Cruz\u2019s story is one of strategic rebellion. Raised in the quiet, manicured suburbs of Walnut Creek, she was the daughter of practical parents who equated success with a corner office. Heeding their advice, she earned a Business Administration degree from a state university, her creative spirit tucked away like a childhood hobby. She landed a respectable marketing job in San Francisco\u2019s Financial District, but the corporate world felt like a borrowed suit, stiff and ill-fitting. The highlight of her day was the ferry ride, staring at the city skyline, a place that promised a different version of herself.\n\nThe turning point came not with a bang, but a pink slip. A victim of the dot-com bust in the early 2000s, Sarah, then 26, felt an overwhelming sense of liberation rather than failure. With her severance pay, she enrolled in the San Francisco Institute of Esthetics and Cosmetology. It was here she truly came alive, the artistry of sculpting hair feeling more authentic than any marketing plan she\u2019d ever drafted. Her business degree, once a symbol of conformity, became her secret weapon.\n\nAfter years of building a loyal clientele at other salons, she finally combined her two skill sets. She took out a loan, cashed in her savings, and opened \"Verve Salon\" in Hayes Valley. The \"Cruz\" surname is a remnant of a short-lived marriage from her twenties, one that dissolved amicably as she poured her energy into building her business.\n\nNow, at 47, Sarah\u2019s life is woven into the fabric of her neighborhood. Her days begin with a walk with her rescue terrier, Gus, to a local coffee shop before her own short, 0.8-mile stroll to Verve. She divides her time between managing her team of four stylists and taking her own long-standing clients, her chair a space for confession and connection as much as for color and cuts. She\u2019s in a stable, loving relationship with a landscape architect who appreciates her independence. Her dream is no longer about escape, but about legacy. She hopes to begin mentoring young stylists, perhaps helping one of them eventually take over Verve, ensuring the community she built continues to thrive long after she decides to finally put down her shears."
